### CSS Float

**float** pushes an element to one side, letting content wrap around it.

---

### Float Values

| Value | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| `none` | Default - no floating |
| `left` | Floats to the left |
| `right` | Floats to the right |
| `inline-start` | Floats to start of text direction |
| `inline-end` | Floats to end of text direction |

---

### Basic Usage

```css
img {
  float: left;
  margin-right: 15px;
}
```

Text wraps around the floated image.

---

### How Float Works

- Element is **removed from normal flow**
- Shifts to left or right edge
- **Following content** wraps around it
- Other block elements ignore it
- **Inline content** (text) wraps around

---

### Float for Layout (Legacy)

Before Flexbox and Grid, float was used for layouts:

```css
.sidebar {
  float: left;
  width: 25%;
}

.main {
  float: left;
  width: 75%;
}
```

**Note:** Modern CSS uses `flexbox` or `grid` instead.

---

### Float with Images

```css
.article img {
  float: left;
  margin: 0 20px 10px 0;
  max-width: 50%;
}

.article img.right {
  float: right;
  margin: 0 0 10px 20px;
}
```

---

### Float Problems

Float can cause **parent collapse** (parent has zero height):

```css
.parent {
  border: 1px solid black;
  /* Parent collapses because children are floated */
}

.child {
  float: left;
  height: 100px;
}
```

**Solution:** Use clearfix (see `clear` file).

> **Modern Take:** Use `flexbox` or `grid` for layout. `float` is only for wrapping text around images.
